Roger D. Nelson (rdnelson@flagstaff.princeton.edu) wrote:
: Onyx Computers uses for the Pentium a Gigabyte GA-586AS, PCI Bus
: Motherboard, and the SiS 85C50X chipset.  These are not household names,

Well, as far as Pentiums go, I've heard really negative things about all
sorts of other chipsets, but I hear that the Intel ones and the SiS ones
are the only ones holding ground.  Still, I'd ask exactly where they get
their motherboard from.  Find out who really manufactures it.  

: systems that are suitable for Linux (unix), have assembled excellent
: components, including Wester Digital HD, TEAC CD and Floppy, and provide
: a choice of sophisticated video boards.  All for very reasonable prices
: that save $200 or more for the system compared to, say Gateway or Dell.
: The Gigabyte motherboard has a 3-yr warranty, as does the WD HD, so the
: company exhibits confidence.

Err...I run Linux and if you want it to run like a dream, you DON'T want
Teac CDROM drive.  I also assume that the Western Digital HD is EIDE?
Bad news...SCSI is the way to go if you're gonna run any Linux stuff.  It
just likes it better and SCSI is bus mastering..EIDE is not.

As for they having confidence, maybe they are just cocky.  but take it from
me, they are not giving you a lower price because they are nice people.
I bought one of my systems from a "smaller" company instead of Gateway
or Dell.  I know how they make it cheaper.  They give you a cheaper monitor,
and stiff you on stuff that you didn't even know you needed.  For example,
when I got my system, they put a crappy serial card in...had problems with it
since it doesn't like my modem...'cause it was crap..had to get a new one
with a 16550 UART.  Little things like that.  If you'd like any more info
on how these companies do this, e-mail me.  I'll be happy to sure with
you my pains and sorrows of mail order.

: While we're at it, what does the net know of Focus keyboards?  Are they
: quiet and clean, or are they flimsy?

I use a Focus keyboard now.  It's pretty sturdy.  It's got a little
calculator which is also the keypad..kinda nifty...haven't had a problem.
It is a clicky keyboard instead of the mushy kind...it's all preference.

